        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>May 2. 1873</date>
                    <salute>Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for your kindness in having sent me the account of the silk-worms, which I have read with great interest.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I quite agree with your remarks on the benefit derived from a change of conditions.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> You do not state that you require the Gazette to be returned, &amp; I will therefore keep it unless I hear to the contrary—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5507.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Isidoro Dell’Oro’s</ref> ‘Sericulture, and silk in Japan and in Europe’, <hi rend="italic">London Gazette</hi>, 17 January 1873, pp. 169–75.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Dell’Oro believed that a change of locality, climate, and rearing practices would help save the eggs from the superior-quality yellow silk cocoons found in Italy, which were subject to a disease (pebrine) that caused larval atrophy; to test his views, he took yellow cocoons from Italy to Japan (<hi rend="italic">London Gazette</hi>, 17 January 1873, pp. 172–3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">There is no copy of the article from the <hi rend="italic">London Gazette</hi> (see n. 1, above) in the Darwin Archive–CUL.</note>
        </div>        
            
